\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Output: rxnorm-output.ttl (A valid Turtle RDF file representing the drug graph).Tool 3: ROBOT (The Ontology Master Tool)Purpose: ROBOT is the "Swiss Army Knife" of ontology engineering. It handles Merging, Reasoning, and Verification. It is the most important tool in the pipeline.Source: ontodev/robotDocker Image: obolibrary/robot:latestStep 3a: Merge (Unification)First, we combine our different ontologies into one graph.robot merge \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--input snomed-output.owl \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--input rxnorm-output.ttl \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--input loinc-output.owl \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--output merged-ontology.owl
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Step 3b: Reason (Inference & Materialization)This is where the "Semantic Magic" happens. We run a Reasoner (like ELK) to compute the class hierarchy. This pre-calculates "Amoxicillin is an Antibiotic" so GraphDB doesn't have to do it during every query.robot reason \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--input merged-ontology.owl \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--reasoner ELK \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--materialize-scopes "subClassOf" \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--output reasoned-ontology.owl
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Step 3c: Verify (The Validation Gate)This corresponds to the "Validate" step in your workflow. We use robot verify to run logical tests.Input: reasoned-ontology.owlInput: queries/validation.sparql (A directory of SPARQL queries that check for errors).Example Validation Query (check_missing_labels.sparql):# ERROR if a Class has no label
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 SELECT ?cls WHERE \{
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0?cls a owl:Class .
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0FILTER NOT EXISTS \{ ?cls rdfs:label ?label \}
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \}
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Execution Command:robot verify \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--input reasoned-ontology.owl \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--queries queries/validation.sparql \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0--output-dir results/
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Result: If this command finds any results (errors), the CI/CD pipeline FAILS. The bad data never leaves the build server.Phase 2: The Load (Writing to Authoritative Core)Once robot verify passes, we have a pristine file: reasoned-ontology.owl.The Action: The CI/CD pipeline uses the GraphDB Preload Tool (or REST API) to push this file.# Using GraphDB's high-performance 'importrdf' utility
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 # This is much faster than standard REST API for bulk loads
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 ./graphdb-importrdf \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0--force \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0--config production-repo-config.ttl \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0--default-graph "graph://kernels/v2025-03" \\
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 \'a0\'a0\'a0reasoned-ontology.owl
\f1\fs24 \

\f0\fs29\fsmilli14667 Validation: Finally, we run a quick count check via curl to the GraphDB SPARQL endpoint to confirm the number of triples loaded matches our expectation.Summary of the "3 Tools"SNOMED-OWL-Toolkit: Translates SNOMED RF2 $\\rightarrow$ OWL.Custom Python Script: Translates RxNorm RRF $\\rightarrow$ RDF (Turtle).ROBOT: Merges, Reasons (Infers), and Validates the final graph.This is a robust, automated engineering pipeline that treats "Knowledge" as "Code," ensuring that only valid, compiled ontologies ever reach your production database.
